stylometry: The data mining method we used was data clustering. In my problem I took a group of 20 horses that needed to be turned out for exercise together in 4 paddocks. First I gathered the data I would need to properly organize the horses (such as behavior, and turnout time needed) in the form of numeric values. This is so I would be able to organize the data. Then I standardized the data to assign simplified values to each horse. This is important because it is the first step in finding the distance between each animal. After that, I applied the Euclidean distance formula for the sum of the squared distances in order to designate a value to each horse. This is important because it helps determine the cluster values. Then, I took the most "average" horses, and assigned them as "cluster centers" to each of the paddocks. This is important because these are the values the other horses will be grouped against. Finally, I assigned each horse to a "cluster center" paddock group, which gives me my final turnout list result.
